I really liked the basic premise of this movie: that an autistic girl, obsessed with martial arts films and living in what seems to be a kickboxing district, could become a fighter of supernatural skill. I also liked:

-How Thai factory owners are universally portrayed as thug-commanding, bull-headed video game bosses;
-How you could feel the strain in the movie's attempt to even-handedly portray the Japanese [Yakuza];
-that, by the point an epileptic 16-year-old in a track suit shows up after twenty grown men have their asses handed to them, you have been made aware that it will be the set piece of the film.


The main character is not called Chocolate, but of course Zen, and is played by the gorgeous Yanin Vismitananda. It only took 4 years for the producers to make her into Brucelle Lee for this movie, which is her first. 46 stars.

Inspired by Wayno's unabating hatchet job on the feminist hero/author Ayd Rand. I, C. G. Leonardo, have resolved to:

1. Read The Fountainhead in its entirety;

2. Read Galt's speech (if I have the time/guts) in Atlas Shrugged;

3. write no less than a monograph and no more than a blog about my experience in so doing.


I have given myself until DECEMBER 31ST, 2009 to accomplish this mission, and invite others to attempt the same, if not something of a similar flavor.

When I asked him recently what he was reading, he named half a dozen books and then a few days later had a press person send me a list of thirteen. Among them were a critique of Keynes (“It’s been proven it doesn’t work, but Keynes was such a brilliant and fascinating guy that he hypnotized this whole generation of economists”); biographies of Booker T. Washington, Peter Drucker, and Ayn Rand (“She wasn’t a business person. And I am. And I know something about the market. And, by telling people that it’s all about selfishness, you’re alienating a huge potential part of the market unnecessarily. She really meant self-interest. Enlightened self-interest. So why use ‘selfishness’? It’s a bad brand”); 

